<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-13T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-13T14:00:00-05:00" n="279" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d279">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">357.AB/12–1351: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gifford</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-13T19:00:00+00:00">December 13, 1951—7 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2730. Subject Kashmir. In meeting Dec 12, <gloss target="#t_CRO1">CRO</gloss> concurred <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss>
                                view that until elections over in India it will be impossible get
                                any substantial concessions from <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss>. Therefore some way must be found bridge gap between
                                Graham’s report and end of January when elections over. Impossible
                                in circumstances avoid <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> res which
                                critical of India and which contains recommendations for concrete
                                action.</p>
                            <p>UK wld favor res containing recommendations to both parties and
                                asking them consider fully and thereafter report back to <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>, perhaps within given time limit.
                                This view of course dependent on whether Graham report lends itself
                                to such treatment; it shld not, for example, be too condemnatory of
                                India.</p>
                            <p>Tel along above lines will probably be sent Paris tomorrow.</p>
                            <p>Rptd info priority Paris 1266, New Delhi 57, Karachi 50.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Gifford</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>